# XIS Agent Notes

This repository treats Markdown documentation as the canonical knowledge source.

## Documentation Layers

- `README.md` is the public GitHub entry point for XIS users.
- `docs/user/*` is user-facing documentation. Organize it by public API behavior and workflows.
- `docs/user/advanced/*` is for optional or specialized capabilities. Do not present client-side storage as a core
  requirement; it is a convenience feature because applications can also keep state on the server.
- Module README files are mostly for framework developers and maintainers.
- `docs/framework/*` is cross-module maintainer documentation.
- `docs/agent/*` contains agent-specific rules.

## Source Material

The old documentation app lives in `docs-app` or `/Users/bernd/projects/xis-docs`. It is source material only. Do not
copy its structure blindly into Markdown.

## Runtime Sources For Template Documentation

When documenting XIS template behavior, verify the current runtime sources before treating old docs as authoritative:

- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/init/DomNormalizer.js`: framework elements, attribute syntax, and normalization
  between tag and attribute forms.
- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/init/HandlerBuilder.js`: which normalized elements and attributes receive runtime
  behavior, such as page links, frontlet links, action links, action buttons, forms, inputs, and submit controls.
- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/parse/ELFunctions.js`: built-in expression-language functions.

Use the old documentation app for editorial structure and examples, but use these runtime files to confirm what actually
exists.

## Template Completion Rule

Template behavior is only really done when all three layers agree:

- runtime code supports the behavior
- integration tests cover what the Java action/model side receives or renders
- `docs/user/*` explains the public behavior with copyable examples

For template features that exist in both forms, always think in pairs:

- attribute syntax, for example `<input xis:binding="name">`
- element syntax, for example `<xis:input binding="name">`

Both forms are worth testing because `DomNormalizer.js` can break one while the other still works.

For form controls, tests should assert what reaches the `@Action` method through `@FormData`, not merely that a DOM value
changed or a request-like payload was assembled. Repeated bindings are intentional: multiple controls with the same
binding can submit multiple values into a Java collection.

## Example Discipline

Documentation examples are part of the public API.

When documenting public behavior:

- include copyable Java examples
- include matching HTML templates when relevant
- prefer examples that can become tests
- avoid pseudocode for annotation names, template attributes, and file locations

The long-term goal is that documented examples are executable or covered by the test suite.

## Collaboration Discipline

Treat user statements about desired documentation structure as strong input, not as unquestioned final architecture.
Check them against the codebase, the old documentation, and the reader's path. If the user points out a missing concept,
make sure it appears where a reader would naturally look, even if the detailed material lives on a separate page.

## Website Policy

A documentation website may be built later, including a project wizard. The website should render or import the
Markdown documentation instead of becoming a second manually maintained copy.
